    "location": "Wet market, Sham Shui Po",
    "context": "Hong Kong wet markets (街市) sell fresh produce, meat, and fish every morning. Vendors are fast-talking and friendly — they appreciate customers who try Cantonese. Get there before 10am for the best picks.",
    "cultural_note": "The \"wet\" in wet market refers to the constant hosing-down of floors to keep fish and meat fresh: the sound of running water is the ambient soundtrack of every Hong Kong market morning. Older Hongkongers refuse to buy fish that isn't still swimming in a tank. The concept of 新鮮 (san1 sin1, freshness) is a standard, not a preference. Many wet market vendors have held the same stall across three generations, and a loyal customer who greets them by name will often find something extra slipped into the bag.",
